04763nam a22006135i 9780822387206DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223872067 a10.1515/97808223872062doi  a(DE-B1597)552186  a(OCoLC)1226678340  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE184.A1bH344 2005 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a305.8/009731 aHartigan Jr., John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOdd Tribes :bToward a Cultural Analysis of White People /cJohn Hartigan Jr. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (370 p.) :b3 photos, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I -- t1. Picturing the Underclass: Myth Making in the Inner City -- t2. Blood Will Tell: The Nationalization of White Trash -- t3. Unpopular Culture: The Case of White Trash -- t4. Reading Trash: Deliverance and the Cultural Poetics of White Trash -- t5. Talking Trash: White Poverty and Marked Forms of Whiteness -- t6. Green Ghettos and the White Underclass -- tPART 2 -- t7. Establishing the Fact of Whiteness -- t8. Locating White Detroit -- t9. Object Lessons in Whiteness: Antiracism and the Study of White Folks -- t10. Cultural Analysis: The Case of Race -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOdd Tribes challenges theories of whiteness and critical race studies by examining the tangles of privilege, debasement, power, and stigma that constitute white identity. Considering the relation of phantasmatic cultural forms such as the racial stereotype "white trash" to the actual social conditions of poor whites, John Hartigan Jr. generates new insights into the ways that race, class, and gender are fundamentally interconnected. By tracing the historical interplay of stereotypes, popular cultural representations, and the social sciences' objectifications of poverty, Hartigan demonstrates how constructions of whiteness continually depend on the vigilant maintenance of class and gender decorums.Odd Tribes engages debates in history, anthropology, sociology, and cultural studies over how race matters. Hartigan tracks the spread of "white trash" from an epithet used only in the South prior to the Civil War to one invoked throughout the country by the early twentieth century. He also recounts how the cultural figure of "white trash" influenced academic and popular writings on the urban poor from the 1880s through the 1990s. Hartigan's critical reading of the historical uses of degrading images of poor whites to ratify lines of color in this country culminates in an analysis of how contemporary performers such as Eminem and Roseanne Barr challenge stereotypical representations of "white trash" by claiming the identity as their own. Odd Tribes presents a compelling vision of what cultural studies can be when diverse research methodologies and conceptual frameworks are brought to bear on pressing social issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aPoorzUnited States. 0aPovertyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aRedneckszUnited States. 0aWhites in popular culturezUnited States. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited States. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxEconomic conditions. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aWorking class whiteszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387206zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387206423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/cov